<P>
 Milhizer, in his second season, sees his team as a two-edged sword. While he 
believes his offense is strong in the skilled positions, he fears the offensive 
line could be hampered by inexperience. Milhizer's sights are on league and 
Southern Section championships. And with second-team all-league quarterback 
Berg, first-teamer Yoo at tailback and free safety, and second-team wide 
receiver McIntosh leading the way, Milhizer's goals might be attainable. In 
addition, the Highlanders are counting on six returning starters and 10 
returning lettermen to keep things rolling. Milhizer said there also seems to 
be a lot of motivation going on between his players. Yoo has told him that he 
wants to be the most inspirational player on the team. "Not MVP, but 
inspirational," Milhizer said. The Highlanders expect tough competition from 
Sonora and Troy, "but don't count out Sunny Hills," Milhizer said. "You can't 
discount the three (Southern Section) championships under (Coach) Tim Devaney." 
</P>
