<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL PREVIEW; VILLAGE CHRISTIAN LYING IN WAIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAIGE A. LEECH, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Village Christian High football Coach Mike Plaisance thinks he's pulling a 
fast one on his rival Alpha League coaches. 
</P>
<P>
 Nearly every coach in the league picks L.A. Baptist -- a team that was 13-0 
and won the Southern Section Division X title last season -- as the team to 
beat. Guess who started the campaign? "They went undefeated last year and won 
it all. They have to be the favorite," said Plaisance, punctuating his 
statement with a hearty laugh. 
</P>
<P>
 Divert the attention, that's his game plan. Let no one know that 14 starters 
return for his team, including kicker Ignacio Brache who booted a 54-yard field 
goal last season. Keep the spotlight on L.A. Baptist. So what if only three 
starters return for the Knights? 
</P>
<P>
 "You don't become the heavyweight champion until you knock out the (reigning 
champion)," Plaisance said, laughing once more. 
</P>
<P>
 Don't be fooled by Plaisance, the league's dean of coaches, who begins his 
15th season with the Crusaders. Village Christian is poised to laugh all the 
way to the league championship and then some. 
</P>
<P>
 L.A. Baptist Coach Mark Bates, who once played for Plaisance at Village 
Christian, sees right through his mentor's ploy. He laughs at the suggestion 
that the Knights are favored. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think so," Bates said. "(Village Christian) is loaded." 
</P>
<P>
 Among Crusader returnees are tailback Jake Funk (1,394 yards rushing, 13 
touchdowns) and fullback Enrique Borja (581 yards), who formed the league's 
most productive backfield last season. 
</P>
<P>
 And even if Funk and Borja can drive the Crusaders only as far as midfield, 
expect to see Brache jogging out with tee in hand to put a few points on the 
scoreboard. 
</P>
<P>
 Brache has made 61 of 65 extra points in two seasons and kicked nine field 
goals last year, five of which traveled 40 yards or more. Several Pacific 10 
Conference colleges already have expressed interest in him. 
</P>
<P>
 Village Christian has a solid team, and Plaisance knows it. 
</P>
<P>
 But with three new coaches and a new team in the league, he relishes playing a 
shell game. He's a self-confessed sneak. "My wife says that too," he cracked. 
</P>
<P>
 Plaisance's sneakiness might pay off against new coaches Gil Crook of Marshall 
Fundamental and Keith Patefield of Maranatha. But the league's other three 
coaches -- including Glenn Bell of league newcomer Kilpatrick -- aren't buying 
it. 
</P>
<P>
 Although the league balloons from four teams to six this year, it is no secret 
who is holding the cards. 
</P>
<P>
 "Village is always good," said Bell, who has coached against the Crusaders 
four times in the past three years in nonleague and playoff games. Kilpatrick 
is a Los Angeles County-funded school for juvenile offenders in Malibu that has 
been a free-lance team the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mustangs never have returning players, which makes Bell's job the toughest 
in the league. Western Christian Coach Reese Mitchell also refuses to play into 
Plaisance's hand. He knows better.  
</P>
<P>
 Western Christian bowed out of the league last season because of a lack of 
players, but the Fighting Lancers return after a one-year absence -- with about 
20 players. 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell, in his 11th season at Western Christian and third as head coach, 
knows Village Christian and L.A. Baptist set the pace. 
</P>
<P>
 "Working against Mike and Mark the past few years, I missed (playing them)," 
Mitchell said. "They've had some outstanding teams. I missed that last year." 
